# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: servant-haskell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:servant-haskell/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Haskell's semantics are historically based on those of the Miranda programming language, which served to focus the efforts of the initial Haskell working group.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The last formal specification of the language was made in July 2010, while the development of GHC continues to expand Haskell via language extensions.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Haskell is used in academia and industry.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] As of May 2021, Haskell was the 28th most popular programming language by Google searches for tutorials, and made up less than 1% of active users on the GitHub source code repository.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] After the release of Miranda by Research Software Ltd. in 1985, interest in lazy functional languages grew.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] By 1987, more than a dozen non-strict, purely functional programming languages existed.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Miranda was the most widely used, but it was proprietary software.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] At the conference on Functional Programming Languages and Computer Architecture (FPCA '87) in Portland, Oregon, there was a strong consensus that a committee be formed to define an open standard for such languages.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The committee's purpose was to consolidate existing functional languages into a common one to serve as a basis for future research in functional-language design.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Haskell was developed by a committee, attempting to bring together off-the-shelf solutions where possible.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Type classes were first proposed by Philip Wadler and Stephen Blott to address the ad hoc handling of equality types and arithmetic overloading in languages at the time.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] In early versions of Haskell up until and including version 1.2, user interaction and input/output (IO) were handled by both streams-based and continuation-based mechanisms, which were widely considered unsatisfactory.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] In version 1.3, monadic IO was introduced, along with the generalisation of type classes to higher kinds (type constructors).
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Along with "do notation", which provides syntactic sugar for the `Monad` type class, this gave Haskell an effect system that maintained referential transparency and was convenient.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Another notable change in early versions was the moving of the "sequential evaluation" operation `seq` (which creates a data dependency between values, and is used in lazy languages to avoid excessive memory consumption) from a type class to a standard function to make refactoring more practical.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The first version of Haskell ("Haskell 1.0") was defined in 1990.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The committee's efforts resulted in a series of language definitions (1.0, 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, and 1.4).
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] In late 1997, the series culminated in *Haskell 98*, intended to specify a stable, minimal, portable version of the language and an accompanying standard library for teaching, and as a base for future extensions.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The committee expressly welcomed creating extensions and variants of Haskell 98 via adding and incorporating experimental features.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] In February 1999, the Haskell 98 language standard was originally published as *The Haskell 98 Report*.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] In January 2003, a revised version was published as *Haskell 98 Language and Libraries: The Revised Report*.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The language continues to evolve rapidly, with the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) implementation representing the current *de facto* standard.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] In early 2006, the process of defining a successor to the Haskell 98 standard, informally named *Haskell Prime*, began.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] This was intended to be an ongoing incremental process to revise the language definition, producing a new revision up to once per year.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The first revision, named *Haskell 2010*, was announced in November 2009 and published in July 2010.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Haskell 2010 added several well-used and uncontroversial features previously enabled via compiler-specific flags.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The next formal specification had been planned for 2020.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] On 29 October 2021, with GHC version 9.2.1, the GHC2021 extension was released.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] While this is not a formal language spec, it combines several stable, widely used GHC extensions to Haskell 2010.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Haskell features lazy evaluation, lambda expressions, pattern matching, list comprehension, type classes and type polymorphism.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] It is a purely functional programming language, which means that functions generally have no side effects.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] A distinct construct exists to represent side effects, orthogonal to the type of functions.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] A pure function can return a side effect that is subsequently executed, modeling the impure functions of other languages.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Haskell has a strong, static type system based on Hindley–Milner type inference.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Its principal innovation in this area is type classes, originally conceived as a principled way to add overloading to the language, but since finding many more uses.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The construct that represents side effects is an example of a monad: a general framework which can model various computations such as error handling, nondeterminism, parsing and software transactional memory.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] They are defined as ordinary datatypes, but Haskell provides some syntactic sugar for their use.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Haskell has an open, published specification, and multiple implementations exist.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Its main implementation, the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC), is both an interpreter and native-code compiler that runs on most platforms.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] GHC is noted for its rich type system incorporating recent innovations such as generalized algebraic data types and type families.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The Computer Language Benchmarks Game also highlights its high-performance implementation of concurrency and parallelism.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] An active, growing community exists around the language, and more than 5,400 third-party open-source libraries and tools are available in the online package repository *Hackage*.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Using Haskell's Fixed-point combinator allows this function to be written without any explicit recursion.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] As the *Integer* type has arbitrary-precision, this code will compute values such as `factorial 100000` (a 456,574-digit number), with no loss of precision.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] All listed implementations are distributed under open source licenses.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Jan-Willem Maessen, in 2002, and Simon Peyton Jones, in 2003, discussed problems associated with lazy evaluation while also acknowledging the theoretical motives for it.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] In addition to purely practical considerations such as improved performance, they note that lazy evaluation makes it more difficult for programmers to reason about the performance of their code (particularly its space use).
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] In particular it disables type classes by default.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Ben Lippmeier designed Disciple as a strict-by-default (lazy by explicit annotation) dialect of Haskell with a type-and-effect system, to address Haskell's difficulties in reasoning about lazy evaluation and in using traditional data structures such as mutable arrays.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Robert Harper, one of the authors of Standard ML, has given his reasons for not using Haskell to teach introductory programming.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Among these are the difficulty of reasoning about resource use with non-strict evaluation, that lazy evaluation complicates the definition of datatypes and inductive reasoning, and the "inferiority" of Haskell's (old) class system compared to ML's module system.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Haskell's build tool, Cabal, has historically been criticized for poorly handling multiple versions of the same library, a problem known as "Cabal hell".
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] The Stackage server and Stack build tool were made in response to these criticisms.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Cabal has since addressed this problem by borrowing ideas from the package manager Nix, with the new approach becoming the default in 2019.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Clean is a close, slightly older relative of Haskell.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Its biggest deviation from Haskell is in the use of uniqueness types instead of monads for input/output (I/O) and side effects.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Haskell events have been regularly held concurrent with the International Conference on Functional Programming (ICFP) including workshops such as the Haskell Symposium (formerly the Haskell Workshop) and Commercial Users of Functional Programming.
[src:servant-haskell/haskell] Other events include the Haskell Implementors Workshop, ZuriHac in Zurich, and Hac: The Haskell Hackathon.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:servant-haskell/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:servant-haskell/tutorial-index] This is an introductory tutorial to **servant**.
[src:servant-haskell/tutorial-index] Whilst browsing is fine, it makes more sense if you read the sections in order, or at least read the first section before anything else.
[src:servant-haskell/tutorial-index] Any comments, issues or feedback about the tutorial can be submitted to servant’s issue tracker.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:servant-haskell/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:servant-haskell/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
